{
  "State Einstein's second postulate of special relativity.": "",
  "Mass increases with speed": "",
  "Nothing can move": "",
  "The speed of light is the same for all observers": "",
  "Time runs faster for moving observers": "",
  "The speed of light in vacuum (c ≈ 3 × 10⁸ m/s) is the same for all observers, regardless of their motion. The other options — 'Mass increases with speed', 'Time runs faster for moving observers', and 'Nothing can move' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is time dilation?": "",
  "Moving clocks run slow: t = γt₀": "",
  "Moving clocks run fast": "",
  "Time only exists at rest": "",
  "Time stops for all observers": "",
  "Time dilation is a relativistic effect where a moving clock runs slower compared to a stationary observer's clock. The relationship is t = γt₀, where t₀ is the proper time (measured by the moving clock) and γ is the Lorentz factor.": "",
  "What is the Lorentz factor (γ)?": "",
  "γ = mc²": "",
  "γ = 1 − v/c": "",
  "γ = v/c": "",
  "γ = 1/√(1 − v²/c²)": "",
  "The Lorentz factor γ = 1/√(1 − v²/c²) describes relativistic effects. It appears in the equations for time dilation and length contraction. The other options — 'γ = v/c', 'γ = mc²', and 'γ = 1 − v/c' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is the mass-energy equivalence?": "",
  "E = mc²": "",
  "E = mv²": "",
  "E = ½mv²": "",
  "E = mgh": "",
  "Mass-Energy Equivalence : E = mc². The other options — 'E = mv²', 'E = mgh', and 'E = ½mv²' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What happens to γ as v → c?": "",
  "γ → 1": "",
  "γ → c": "",
  "γ → infinity": "",
  "γ → 0": "",
  "The Lorentz factor γ = 1/√(1 - v²/c²) describes relativistic effects. As an object's speed approaches c, γ → ∞, causing time dilation and length contraction. The answer is 'γ → infinity'. The other options — 'γ → 0', 'γ → 1', and 'γ → c' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is length contraction?": "",
  "Moving objects are longer": "",
  "Objects don't change length": "",
  "Moving objects are shorter in the direction of motion": "",
  "Length only changes at rest": "",
  "Length Contraction — Moving objects are shorter in the direction of motion. The other options — 'Moving objects are longer', 'Objects don't change length', and 'Length only changes at rest' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "At everyday speeds, γ is approximately:": "",
  "Exactly 1": "",
  "Equal to c": "",
  "Infinity": "",
  "Exactly 0": "",
  "At everyday speeds, γ ≈ 1 and effects are negligible. The speed of light in vacuum (c ≈ 3 × 10⁸ m/s) is the same for all observers, regardless of their motion. The other options — '0', 'Infinity', and 'c' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is Einstein's first postulate of special relativity?": "",
  "The laws of physics are the same in all inertial reference frames": "",
  "Accelerating objects experience stronger gravitational fields always": "",
  "The speed of light depends on the motion of the light source": "",
  "Energy cannot be created or destroyed in any reference frame": "",
  "Einstein's first postulate states that all the laws of physics are identical in all inertial (non-accelerating) reference frames. No experiment performed inside a closed room can determine whether the room is at rest or moving at constant velocity.": "",
  "What happens to the relativistic momentum of an object as its speed approaches the speed of light?": "",
  "Relativistic momentum approaches zero as speed increases toward c": "",
  "Relativistic momentum remains equal to the classical momentum mv": "",
  "Relativistic momentum approaches infinity as speed approaches c": "",
  "Relativistic momentum decreases and eventually becomes negative": "",
  "Relativistic momentum is p = γmv. As v approaches c, γ approaches infinity, so the momentum also approaches infinity. This is why no object with mass can actually reach the speed of light — it would require infinite energy.": "",
  "Can any object with mass travel at the speed of light?": "",
  "Yes, if given enough time to accelerate continuously in space": "",
  "No, because it would require infinite energy to reach the speed of light": "",
  "Yes, but only in a vacuum where there is no friction to slow it down": "",
  "No, because the speed of light only applies to massless sound waves": "",
  "As an object with mass accelerates toward c, its relativistic mass (and the energy required to accelerate it further) increases without bound. Reaching c would require infinite energy, which is impossible. Only massless particles like photons travel at exactly c.": "",
  "What is an 'inertial reference frame' in special relativity?": "",
  "Any reference frame that is accelerating due to an applied net force": "",
  "A reference frame moving at constant velocity with no net force acting": "",
  "A reference frame that is rotating uniformly around a fixed central axis": "",
  "A reference frame that is stationary relative to the center of the Earth": "",
  "An inertial reference frame is one that is not accelerating — it is either at rest or moving at a constant velocity in a straight line. Special relativity applies specifically to inertial frames. Newton's laws hold without modification in inertial frames.": "",
  "Define 'proper time' in the context of special relativity.": "",
  "The time interval measured by a clock at rest relative to the event being timed": "",
  "The time measured by any clock regardless of its state of motion or location": "",
  "The longest possible time interval that any observer in the universe can measure": "",
  "The time required for light to travel exactly one meter in a complete vacuum": "",
  "Proper time (t₀) is the time interval between two events as measured by an observer who is present at both events (or by a clock at rest relative to the events). It is always the shortest time interval measured by any observer.": "",
  "What does 'proper length' mean in special relativity?": "",
  "The shortest possible length of an object as measured by a moving observer": "",
  "The length of an object measured in the frame where the object is at rest": "",
  "The length of an object after it has been compressed by gravitational forces": "",
  "The length of any object measured from a frame traveling at the speed of light": "",
  "Proper length (L₀) is the length of an object measured in the reference frame where the object is at rest. It is the longest length any observer will measure. Moving observers measure a contracted (shorter) length: L = L₀/γ.": "",
  "What is meant by 'relativistic speed'?": "",
  "Any speed that is slower than the average walking speed of a person": "",
  "A speed so fast that relativistic effects like time dilation become significant": "",
  "A speed that is exactly equal to the speed of light in a perfect vacuum": "",
  "The speed of sound in air, which is used as a reference in relativity": "",
  "A relativistic speed is a speed that is a significant fraction of the speed of light (typically above about 0.1c or 10% of c). At such speeds, the Lorentz factor γ deviates noticeably from 1, and effects like time dilation and length contraction become measurable.": "",
  "Define 'rest energy' using Einstein's mass-energy equivalence.": "",
  "The kinetic energy an object has when it is moving at maximum speed": "",
  "The energy equivalent of an object's mass when it is at rest, given by E₀ = mc²": "",
  "The potential energy stored in an object due to its height above the ground": "",
  "The energy required to bring a moving object completely to a stop from any speed": "",
  "Rest energy (E₀ = mc²) is the energy equivalent of an object's mass when it is stationary. Even at rest, an object possesses an enormous amount of energy due to its mass. This is the energy released in nuclear reactions where mass is converted to energy.": "",
  "What is the 'relativistic mass' concept?": "",
  "The idea that an object's effective mass increases with speed as γm": "",
  "The mass of an object at rest measured on a standard laboratory balance": "",
  "The mass of light, which is always exactly zero regardless of frequency": "",
  "The mass lost by an object when it emits thermal radiation into space": "",
  "Relativistic mass is the concept that an object's effective resistance to acceleration increases with speed according to m_rel = γm, where m is the rest mass. As speed approaches c, relativistic mass approaches infinity, explaining why massive objects cannot reach light speed.": "",
  "What does the term 'simultaneity' mean in special relativity?": "",
  "Two events happening at the same time, which may depend on the observer's reference frame": "",
  "Two events that always occur at the same time for every observer in every frame": "",
  "The phenomenon where time stops completely for observers at the speed of light": "",
  "A principle stating that all clocks in the universe are perfectly synchronized": "",
  "In special relativity, simultaneity is relative — two events that appear simultaneous in one reference frame may not be simultaneous in another frame moving relative to the first. This is called the relativity of simultaneity and is a direct consequence of the constant speed of light.": "",
  "What is a 'light-year' in physics?": "",
  "The amount of time it takes light to travel from the Sun to the Earth": "",
  "The distance that light travels in one year through a vacuum": "",
  "The speed at which light travels measured in kilometers per hour": "",
  "The energy contained in one photon of visible light over one year": "",
  "A light-year is a unit of distance, not time. It is the distance light travels in one year in a vacuum, approximately 9.46 × 10¹² kilometers. It is commonly used in astronomy to express the vast distances between stars and galaxies.": "",
  "What is meant by the 'speed of light limit' in special relativity?": "",
  "Light can only travel at one specific speed, but matter can exceed it": "",
  "Nothing carrying information or mass can travel faster than the speed of light": "",
  "The speed of light is merely a suggestion and can be exceeded in a vacuum": "",
  "Only gravity can travel faster than light according to Einstein's theory": "",
  "Special relativity establishes c (the speed of light in vacuum, approximately 3 × 10⁸ m/s) as the ultimate speed limit. No object with mass, and no signal carrying information, can travel faster than c. This is a fundamental consequence of the structure of spacetime.": "",
  "Define 'spacetime' as used in relativity.": "",
  "A four-dimensional framework combining three dimensions of space with one dimension of time": "",
  "The empty void between galaxies where neither matter nor energy can exist": "",
  "A measurement of how much space an object occupies at a single moment in time": "",
  "The total volume of the observable universe at the current point in time": "",
  "Spacetime is the four-dimensional continuum that merges the three dimensions of space with the single dimension of time into a unified framework. In relativity, space and time are not independent — they are interrelated, and events are described by four coordinates (x, y, z, t).": "",
  "A spaceship travels at 0.8c relative to Earth. An astronaut on board measures the trip as taking 3 years on her clock. Using time dilation (γ = 5/3 at 0.8c), how long does the trip appear to take for an observer on Earth?": "",
  "1.8 years": "",
  "3.0 years": "",
  "5.0 years": "",
  "9.0 years": "",
  "The astronaut measures proper time t₀ = 3 years. The Earth observer measures dilated time t = γt₀ = (5/3)(3) = 5 years. The moving clock (astronaut's) runs slower from Earth's perspective, so more time passes on Earth.": "",
  "A student calculates the rest energy of a 1 kg object using E = mc². Given c = 3 × 10⁸ m/s, she finds E = 9 × 10¹⁶ J. She compares this to the energy from burning about 2 million tons of coal. What does this comparison illustrate?": "",
  "Mass contains a relatively small amount of energy compared to chemical fuels": "",
  "Even a small amount of mass corresponds to an enormous amount of energy": "",
  "Energy and mass are completely unrelated physical quantities in all contexts": "",
  "Coal produces more energy per kilogram than nuclear reactions can produce": "",
  "Because c² is such a large number (9 × 10¹⁶ m²/s²), even 1 kg of mass contains an enormous amount of energy — equivalent to burning millions of tons of coal. This explains why nuclear reactions (which convert small amounts of mass to energy) release so much energy.": "",
  "Muons are subatomic particles created in the upper atmosphere by cosmic rays. They have a very short half-life and should decay before reaching Earth's surface. Yet detectors on the ground observe many muons. What relativistic effect explains this?": "",
  "Muons travel faster than light so they arrive before they have time to decay": "",
  "Time dilation causes the muons' internal clocks to run slower, extending their observed lifetime": "",
  "New muons are created at ground level to replace the ones that decay in flight": "",
  "The muons are actually stationary and the Earth moves up to meet them instead": "",
  "Muons travel at nearly the speed of light. Due to time dilation, their internal 'clocks' run much slower from Earth's perspective, so they survive long enough to reach the ground. From the muon's perspective, length contraction shortens the distance to the ground. Both explanations are consistent.": "",
  "A rocket ship is 100 meters long when measured at rest. It flies past Earth at 0.6c. An observer on Earth measures the rocket's length. Using length contraction with γ = 1.25 at 0.6c, what length does the Earth observer measure?": "",
  "125 meters": "",
  "100 meters": "",
  "80 meters": "",
  "60 meters": "",
  "Length contraction gives L = L₀/γ = 100/1.25 = 80 meters. The Earth observer measures the moving rocket as shorter in the direction of motion. The rocket's crew, however, still measures their ship as 100 meters long in their own rest frame.": "",
  "A student reads that GPS satellites must account for relativistic effects. She wonders why this matters for everyday navigation. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "GPS satellites orbit so fast that their clocks run slightly slower due to time dilation, requiring corrections": "",
  "GPS satellites travel faster than light, causing their signals to arrive before being sent": "",
  "Relativistic effects cause GPS signals to change frequency as they pass through Earth's atmosphere": "",
  "GPS satellites are too small for Newtonian mechanics, so relativity must be used instead": "",
  "GPS satellites move at about 14,000 km/h and experience time dilation (their clocks run slightly slower due to speed) and gravitational effects (their clocks run slightly faster due to weaker gravity). Without relativistic corrections, GPS positions would drift by kilometers per day.": "",
  "Two students are debating. Student A claims that if you could travel at the speed of light, time would stop for you. Student B says that is impossible. Who is correct and why?": "",
  "Student A is correct because time literally stops at the speed of light for all objects": "",
  "Student B is correct because objects with mass cannot reach the speed of light": "",
  "Both are wrong because time dilation only applies to objects larger than an atom": "",
  "Student A is correct because astronauts have already traveled at the speed of light": "",
  "Student B is correct. While the time dilation formula shows t → ∞ as v → c (suggesting time effectively stops), no object with mass can actually reach c because it would require infinite energy. Only massless particles like photons travel at c.": "",
  "A particle physicist accelerates a proton to 0.99c in a particle accelerator. She notices that the proton requires much more energy to accelerate from 0.99c to 0.999c than it did from 0.9c to 0.99c. Why?": "",
  "The accelerator becomes less efficient at higher speeds due to electrical resistance": "",
  "As speed approaches c, the Lorentz factor increases rapidly, requiring dramatically more energy": "",
  "The proton's charge decreases at higher speeds, making it harder to accelerate": "",
  "Friction with vacuum particles increases exponentially at near-light speeds": "",
  "As speed approaches c, the Lorentz factor γ increases dramatically (γ ≈ 7.09 at 0.99c but γ ≈ 22.4 at 0.999c). Since the total energy is E = γmc², the energy needed to increase speed grows enormously as v gets closer to c.": "",
  "A student learns about the 'twin paradox.' One twin stays on Earth while the other travels at high speed to a distant star and returns. When they reunite, the traveling twin is younger. Why is this not a contradiction, since each twin sees the other as moving?": "",
  "It is a true paradox with no resolution in current physics or relativity theory": "",
  "The traveling twin must accelerate and decelerate, breaking the symmetry between the two frames": "",
  "Both twins actually age at the same rate, and the paradox is just a mathematical error": "",
  "Only the Earth twin experiences time, since the traveling twin is in a vacuum": "",
  "The situation is not truly symmetric. The traveling twin must accelerate to leave, decelerate, turn around, accelerate again, and decelerate to return. These accelerations mean the traveling twin is not always in an inertial frame, breaking the symmetry and making the traveling twin genuinely younger.": "",
  "A student calculates that at v = 0.1c (10% of light speed), the Lorentz factor γ is approximately 1.005. She concludes that relativistic effects are barely noticeable. At what fraction of c do relativistic effects start to become significant?": "",
  "At about 0.001c, where γ differs from 1 by a large amount already": "",
  "Relativistic effects are always significant at every speed above zero": "",
  "At speeds above about 0.1c to 0.3c, where γ starts noticeably deviating from 1": "",
  "Only at exactly c, and at all lower speeds γ is always precisely equal to 1": "",
  "Relativistic effects are technically present at all speeds but become noticeable when γ deviates significantly from 1. At 0.1c, γ ≈ 1.005 (0.5% effect). At 0.3c, γ ≈ 1.048 (about 5% effect). Effects become dramatic above 0.5c, where γ ≈ 1.155.": "",
  "An astronaut traveling at 0.9c shines a flashlight forward. According to classical physics, the light should travel at c + 0.9c = 1.9c relative to Earth. What does special relativity predict instead?": "",
  "The light travels at 1.9c relative to Earth, as classical physics predicts": "",
  "The light travels at exactly c relative to Earth, as it does for all observers": "",
  "The light travels at 0.1c relative to Earth because the ship absorbs most of the speed": "",
  "The light cannot be emitted while the ship is moving at such a high speed": "",
  "Einstein's second postulate states that the speed of light is the same for all observers, regardless of their motion. An Earth observer would measure the flashlight beam traveling at exactly c, not 1.9c. Velocities do not add simply at relativistic speeds — the relativistic velocity addition formula must be used.": ""
